<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12368&amp;p=140976#p140976</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12368&amp;p=140976#p140976"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: What is a .ips file?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12368&amp;p=140976#p140976"><![CDATA[
I stated the two reasons in my previous post. Let me expand:<br /><br />The first is size. The IPS file might be smaller than an already-patched ROM. This was arguably more important in the dial-up era when a 56K modem would take 15 minutes to move a 32 Mbit (4 MB) ROM. And a lot of people are still stuck on pay-per-bit Internet, such as satellite or cellular, that charges $5 or more per GB.<br /><br />The other is liability reasons. It is believed that the legal counsel of the games' publishers pursues people who distribute already-patched ROMs more than people who distribute patches.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Tue Feb 10, 2015 8:10 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
