<author><name><![CDATA[tepples]]></name></author>
<updated>2015-02-10T17:57:19-07:00</updated>
<published>2015-02-10T17:57:19-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12368&amp;p=140968#p140968</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12368&amp;p=140968#p140968"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: What is a .ips file?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12368&amp;p=140968#p140968"><![CDATA[
<a href="http://zerosoft.zophar.net/ips.php" class="postlink">IPS</a> is a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patch_%28computing%29" class="postlink">patch</a> format that stores differences between two binary files. Say someone has A.bin and B.bin, puts them into a differencing program to produce A_to_B.ips, and sends you a copy of A_to_B.ips. You obtain A.bin elsewhere. Then you can put A.bin and A_to_B.ips into a patching program to produce a copy of B.bin.<br /><br /><strong>Why patch?</strong> People distribute A_to_B.ips instead of B.bin to minimize the amount of data they have to send, whether for bandwidth reasons or in an attempt to qualify for the &quot;amount and substantiality&quot; test under copyright exceptions.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Tue Feb 10, 2015 5:57 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
